				<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body" aria-labelledby="firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-container>
					<div class="vector-body-before-content">
							<div class="mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id="contentSub"><div id="mw-content-subtitle"><span class="mw-redirectedfrom">(Redirected from <a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissel&amp;redirect=no" class="mw-redirect" title="Israel Bissel">Israel Bissel</a>)</span></div></div>
					
					
					<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content"><div class="mw-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about the Patriot post rider who made a southerly route from Boston to New York and likely Philadelphia to sound the alarm about the <a href="/wiki/Battle_of_Lexington" class="mw-redirect" title="Battle of Lexington">Battle of Lexington</a>. For the rider who carried the dispatch west of Boston and then to <a href="/wiki/Hartford,_Connecticut" title="Hartford, Connecticut">Hartford, Connecticut</a>, see <a href="/wiki/Isaac_Bissell" title="Isaac Bissell">Isaac Bissell</a>.</div>
<table class="infobox biography vcard"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-above"><div class="fn">Israel Bissell</div></th></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Born</th><td class="infobox-data">1752<br /><div style="display:inline" class="birthplace"><a href="/wiki/East_Windsor,_Connecticut" title="East Windsor, Connecticut">East Windsor, Connecticut</a>, <a href="/wiki/Connecticut_Colony" title="Connecticut Colony">Connecticut Colony</a>, <a href="/wiki/British_America" title="British America">British America</a></div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Died</th><td class="infobox-data">October 24, 1823<span style="display:none">(1823-10-24)</span> (aged&#160;71)<br /><div style="display:inline" class="deathplace"><a href="/wiki/Hinsdale,_Massachusetts" title="Hinsdale, Massachusetts">Hinsdale, Massachusetts</a>, United States</div></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Other&#160;names</th><td class="infobox-data nickname">Israel Bissel</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Occupation(s)</th><td class="infobox-data role"><a href="/wiki/Post_riders" title="Post riders">Post rider</a>, <a href="/wiki/Minutemen" title="Minutemen">colonial militia officer</a></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Spouse</th><td class="infobox-data">Lucy Hancock (1784–1823; his death)</td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Children</th><td class="infobox-data">4</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p><b>Israel Bissell</b>, also spelled <b>Bissel</b> (1752&#160;– October 24, 1823), was a <a href="/wiki/Patriot_(American_Revolution)" title="Patriot (American Revolution)">patriot</a> <a href="/wiki/Post_riders" title="Post riders">post rider</a> who delivered mail between <a href="/wiki/Boston" title="Boston">Boston</a>, <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts" title="Massachusetts">Massachusetts</a> and <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York</a>.
</p><p>On April 19, 1775, <a href="/wiki/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord" title="Battles of Lexington and Concord">British fired on colonists in Lexington and Concord</a>, inciting the <a href="/wiki/American_Revolutionary_War" title="American Revolutionary War">American Revolutionary War</a>. Bissell was assigned to alert <a href="/wiki/Colonial_history_of_the_United_States" title="Colonial history of the United States">American colonists</a> the news and rally them to assist the Massachusetts <a href="/wiki/Minutemen" title="Minutemen">minutemen</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Lexington_Alarm" title="Lexington Alarm">Lexington Alarm</a> message was carried by Bissell through eastern Massachusetts, <a href="/wiki/Connecticut" title="Connecticut">Connecticut</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_Jersey" title="New Jersey">New Jersey</a>, and ultimately to <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia" title="Philadelphia">Philadelphia</a>, <a href="/wiki/Pennsylvania" title="Pennsylvania">Pennsylvania</a>.
</p><p>The order stated that Bissell was to travel through Connecticut, which he did, traveling along the <a href="/wiki/Boston_Post_Road" title="Boston Post Road">Old Post Road</a> from <a href="/wiki/Watertown,_Massachusetts" title="Watertown, Massachusetts">Watertown, Massachusetts</a> to <a href="/wiki/New_Haven" class="mw-redirect" title="New Haven">New Haven</a>, where the dispatch included an order to take the message to Philadelphia. In New York, General <a href="/wiki/Alexander_McDougall" title="Alexander McDougall">Alexander McDougall</a> added an order to obtain a new rider to convey the message to Philadelphia. According to the <a href="/wiki/Sons_of_the_American_Revolution" title="Sons of the American Revolution">Sons of the American Revolution</a> and Elizabeth Norton Hunt, Bissell went the entire way to Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Along the way, Bissell shouted "To arms, to arms, the war has begun", and carried a message from <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Palmer_(American_Revolutionary_War_general)" title="Joseph Palmer (American Revolutionary War general)">Joseph Palmer</a> asking townspeople to send soldiers to the fight.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Chapman_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Benedict_Arnold" title="Benedict Arnold">Benedict Arnold</a> of <a href="/wiki/New_Haven,_Connecticut" title="New Haven, Connecticut">New Haven</a>, <a href="/wiki/Israel_Putnam" title="Israel Putnam">Israel Putnam</a> of Pomfret, and others mustered soldiers and headed for the battlegrounds in Massachusetts.
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_life">Early life</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Early life"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Israel Bissell was born in 1752 in <a href="/wiki/East_Windsor,_Connecticut" title="East Windsor, Connecticut">East Windsor</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Connecticut_Colony" title="Connecticut Colony">Connecticut Colony</a> of the <a href="/wiki/British_colonization_of_the_Americas" title="British colonization of the Americas">British Colonies</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> He was the son of Israel Bissell Sr.<sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;a&#93;</a></sup> His family settled in East Windsor after they immigrated from England.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg/220px-The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="146" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg/330px-The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg/440px-The_Shot_Heard_%27Round_the_World_by_Domenick_D%27Andrea.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4369" data-file-height="2903" /></a><figcaption>Domenick D'Andrea, <i>The Shot Heard 'Round the World</i>, <a href="/wiki/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord" title="Battles of Lexington and Concord">Battles of Lexington and Concord</a>, April 19, 1775</figcaption></figure>
<p>Bissell was a <a href="/wiki/Post_riders" title="Post riders">post rider</a> who carried mail between Boston and New York<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> for the British Crown (subject to decisions made by King <a href="/wiki/George_III" title="George III">George III</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Parliament_of_Great_Britain" title="Parliament of Great Britain">British Parliament</a>). When the British fired <a href="/wiki/Benjamin_Franklin" title="Benjamin Franklin">Benjamin Franklin</a> from the post of <a href="/wiki/United_States_Postmaster_General" title="United States Postmaster General">Postmaster General</a> for the British Colonies, the <a href="/wiki/Patriot_(American_Revolution)" title="Patriot (American Revolution)">Patriots</a> established mail routes. Bissell worked for them,<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> transporting the mail, including dispatches for the <a href="/wiki/Sons_of_Liberty" title="Sons of Liberty">Sons of Liberty</a> along the same route.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmith195642_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmith195642-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> In preparation for a war, the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_safety_(American_Revolution)" title="Committee of safety (American Revolution)">Massachusetts Committee of Safety</a> chose Bissel to carry the <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/call_to_arms" class="extiw" title="wikt:call to arms">call to arms</a> from Watertown when the war began.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Lexington_Alarm"><span class="anchor" id="Lexington_Alarm"></span>Lexington Alarm</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Lexington Alarm"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dispatch">Dispatch</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Dispatch"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>On April 19, 1775, <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Palmer_(American_Revolutionary_War_general)" title="Joseph Palmer (American Revolutionary War general)">Joseph Palmer</a> of the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_Safety_(American_Revolution)" class="mw-redirect" title="Committee of Safety (American Revolution)">Committee of Safety</a> sent Israel Bissell on a ride through Connecticut<sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> to warn colonists that the war with Britain had begun.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-DAB_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DAB-15">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> The purpose of the dispatch was to have militias in five colonies rally to support the <a href="/wiki/Minutemen" title="Minutemen">minutemen</a> of the <a href="/wiki/List_of_militia_units_of_Massachusetts" title="List of militia units of Massachusetts">Massachusetts militia</a> at the <a href="/wiki/Battles_of_Lexington_and_Concord" title="Battles of Lexington and Concord">Battles of Lexington and Concord</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Chapman_4-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bissell carried the "call to arms" message to Worcester, south and west through Connecticut, and ultimately to Philadelphia. The New York copy of the dispatch stated:<sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class="templatequote"><div style="float: right;">Watertown, Wednesday near<br />10 o'Clock, 19th April 1775.</div><p><br /><br />To all the friends of American liberty be it known that this morning before break of day, a brigade, consisting of about 1,000 to 1,200 men landed at Phip's Farm, at Cambridge, and marched to Lexington, where they found a company of our colony militia in arms, upon whom they fired without any provocation, killed six men and wounded four others. — By an express from Boston, we find another brigade are now upon their march from Boston, supposed to be about 1,000. The Bearer, Israel Bissell, is charged to alarm the country quite to Connecticut, and all persons are desired to furnish him with fresh horses, as they may be needed. — I have spoken with several persons who have seen the dead and wounded; pray let the delegates from this colony to Connecticut see this, they know Col. Foster of Brookfield one of the delegates.</p><div class="templatequotecite">—&#8202;<cite>J. Palmer, one of the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_Safety_(American_Revolution)" class="mw-redirect" title="Committee of Safety (American Revolution)">Committee of Safety</a><sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></cite></div></blockquote>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Hutchison-Post-Rider_(cropped).jpg" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="133" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg/330px-Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg/440px-Hutchison-Post-Rider_%28cropped%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="5124" data-file-height="3108" /></a><figcaption>David Hutchison, <i>The Post Rider Brings News of the Battle of Lexington,</i> mural for the United States Post Office in <a href="/wiki/New_Rochelle,_New_York" title="New Rochelle, New York">New Rochelle, New York</a>, 1940</figcaption></figure>
<p>Bissell left Palmer and traveled to Worcester, passing many people walking towards Lexington.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Along the way, Bissell shouted "To arms, to arms, the war has begun"<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> and "the war has begun, the war has begun".<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Townspeople rang church bells and fired cannons to alert neighboring colonists.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bissell averaged about 69 miles (111&#160;km) per day<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> on the 345 miles (555&#160;km) journey,<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Chapman_4-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmith195642_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmith195642-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;c&#93;</a></sup> requiring him to obtain fresh horses along the route.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> According to tradition, Bissell's horse was exhausted after the first leg from Watertown to Worcester.<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Bissell said to have made the trip within two hours, crossing a distance of 36 miles (58&#160;km) that was generally one <sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> or two days travel for a post rider.<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;d&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Scheide states that Bissell may have arrived in Worcester in the late afternoon or evening and rested overnight to get to Brooklyn by 11 a.m. on April 20, 1775.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Francoeur_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Francoeur-20">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Sons_of_the_American_Revolution" title="Sons of the American Revolution">Sons of the American Revolution</a> state that Bissell left Worcester for Connecticut on the morning of April 20, 1775,<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Monroe Stearns said, "Bissell rode so hard that his horse dropped dead in Worcester that night. The next morning he got a fresh horse, and rode on."<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStearns196784_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEStearns196784-21">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;e&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As stated in the notice, Bissell was to ride throughout Connecticut,<sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> and yet he delivered the message to New York and ultimately to Philadelphia,<sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–69_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–69-23">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> where the <a href="/wiki/Continental_Congress" title="Continental Congress">Continental Congress</a> convened.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194057_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194057-24">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<table class="infobox" style="clear: right; float:right;margin:0 0 1.5em 1.5em"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-above" style="font-size:115%">Images of the dispatches, with attestations, from <i>The Lexington Alarm</i> by John Scheide</th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="text-align: left"><span typeof="mw:File"><span><img alt="image icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" decoding="async" width="16" height="16" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></span></span> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.americanantiquarian.org/proceedings/44807014.pdf">Handwritten dispatch at Norwich, Connecticut, see the image between pages 50 and 51</a></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="text-align: left"><span typeof="mw:File"><span><img alt="image icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" decoding="async" width="16" height="16" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></span></span> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.americanantiquarian.org/proceedings/44807014.pdf">Handwritten dispatch at Elizabethtown, New Jersey, see the image between pages 66 and 67</a></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="text-align: left"><span typeof="mw:File"><span><img alt="image icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" decoding="async" width="16" height="16" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></span></span> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.americanantiquarian.org/proceedings/44807014.pdf">A portion of the handwritten dispatch at Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, see the image between pages 56 and 57</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Bissell generally had to convince the townspeople that the dispatch was not a false alarm.<sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> The dispatch was copied for the town's records, with the original order by Joseph Palmer and attestations of the previous stops.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194057_24-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194057-24">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> Bissell took a break at some of the stops to get a nap and some food<sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> before he took the dispatch for the next stop on his route.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194057_24-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194057-24">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> Townspeople printed the alarm in <a href="/wiki/Broadside_(printing)" title="Broadside (printing)">broadsides</a> and newspapers.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> At New Haven, the dispatch was amended to include an order to take the message on to Philadelphia, "We thought it necessary and expedient to communicate by express, expecting your speedy aid to forward the same to the Congress at Philadelphia..."<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194057_24-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194057-24">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> At New York, the dispatch was amended by General <a href="/wiki/Alexander_McDougall" title="Alexander McDougall">Alexander McDougall</a> to obtain a new rider to convey the message to Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> According to the <a href="/wiki/Sons_of_the_American_Revolution" title="Sons of the American Revolution">Sons of the American Revolution</a>, several historians believe that Israel Bissell rode the entire route to Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> From New York, the message was delivered at stops in New Jersey, before going on to Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063–69_26-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063–69-26">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-28" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">&#91;f&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Timeline">Timeline</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Timeline"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Boston_Post_Road_map.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Boston_Post_Road_map.png/220px-Boston_Post_Road_map.png" decoding="async" width="220" height="145" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Boston_Post_Road_map.png/330px-Boston_Post_Road_map.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e7/Boston_Post_Road_map.png/440px-Boston_Post_Road_map.png 2x" data-file-width="4020" data-file-height="2658" /></a><figcaption>Map of <a href="/wiki/Boston_Post_Road" title="Boston Post Road">Boston Post Roads</a>, showing the Boston and New York roads, 1914</figcaption></figure>
<p>The timeline of the ride is based on the date and the time of the attestations at  Bissell's stops. The attestations meant that the signers understood that the war had begun.<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The stops were:
</p>
<ul><li>April 19, 10 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Watertown,_Massachusetts" title="Watertown, Massachusetts">Watertown, Massachusetts</a><sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;g&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 19, <a href="/wiki/Worcester,_Massachusetts" title="Worcester, Massachusetts">Worcester, Massachusetts</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;h&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 20, <a href="/wiki/Pomfret,_Connecticut" title="Pomfret, Connecticut">Pomfret, Connecticut</a> - Bissell told <a href="/wiki/Israel_Putnam" title="Israel Putnam">Israel Putnam</a>, who was plowing his fields with his son Daniela, that the war had started.<sup id="cite_ref-Francoeur_20-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Francoeur-20">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;i&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 20, 11 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Brooklyn,_Connecticut" title="Brooklyn, Connecticut">Brooklyn, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<table class="infobox" style="clear: right; float:right;margin:0 0 1.5em 1.5em"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-above" style="font-size:115%">External image</th></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="infobox-full-data" style="text-align: left"><span typeof="mw:File"><span><img alt="image icon" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/16px-Searchtool.svg.png" decoding="async" width="16" height="16" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/24px-Searchtool.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/6/61/Searchtool.svg/32px-Searchtool.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="512" data-file-height="512" /></span></span> <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://digitalvgw.omeka.net/exhibits/show/lexington-alarm-letter-exhibit/from-massachusetts-to-ct">"To Christopher Leffingwell Esq. Or Either the Committee of Correspondence – Norwich"</a>, Leffingwell House Museum</td></tr></tbody></table>
<ul><li>April 20, 4 p.m., <a href="/wiki/Norwich,_Connecticut" title="Norwich, Connecticut">Norwich, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194064_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194064-35">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;j&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 20, 7 p.m., <a href="/wiki/New_London,_Connecticut" title="New London, Connecticut">New London, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194064_35-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194064-35">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-39" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-39">&#91;k&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, 1 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Lyme,_Connecticut" title="Lyme, Connecticut">Lyme, Connecticut</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> where he took a ferry across the <a href="/wiki/Connecticut_River" title="Connecticut River">Connecticut River</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, 4 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Old_Saybrook,_Connecticut" title="Old Saybrook, Connecticut">Old Saybrook, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, 7 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Killingworth,_Connecticut" title="Killingworth, Connecticut">Killingworth, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, 8 a.m., <a href="/wiki/East_Guilford,_Connecticut" class="mw-redirect" title="East Guilford, Connecticut">East Guilford, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, 10 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Guilford,_Connecticut" title="Guilford, Connecticut">Guilford, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21, noon, <a href="/wiki/Branford,_Connecticut" title="Branford, Connecticut">Branford, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 21 or 22, <a href="/wiki/New_Haven,_Connecticut" title="New Haven, Connecticut">New Haven, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-41" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-41">&#91;l&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 22, 8 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Fairfield,_Connecticut" title="Fairfield, Connecticut">Fairfield, Connecticut</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065_40-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065-40">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 23, 2 p.m. received per General McDougall, attestation at the 4 p.m. meeting of the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_Sixty" title="Committee of Sixty">Committee of Sixty</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMerritt194692_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMerritt194692-42">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;m&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Wall_Street" title="Wall Street">Wall Street</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–66_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–66-33">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-46" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-46">&#91;n&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 24, <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth,_New_Jersey" title="Elizabeth, New Jersey">Elizabeth, New Jersey</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;o&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;p&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 24, 2 a.m., <a href="/wiki/New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey" title="New Brunswick, New Jersey">New Brunswick, New Jersey</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 24, 6 a.m., <a href="/wiki/Princeton,_New_Jersey" title="Princeton, New Jersey">Princeton, New Jersey</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 24, 9, a.m., <a href="/wiki/Trenton,_New_Jersey" title="Trenton, New Jersey">Trenton, New Jersey</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;q&#93;</a></sup> A message was said to be delivered to Trenton by Comm. Eben Hasard.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>April 24, 5 p.m., <a href="/wiki/Philadelphia" title="Philadelphia">Philadelphia</a><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;r&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;s&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Bissell may have traveled with two horses<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> on the <a href="/wiki/Boston_Post_Road" title="Boston Post Road">Upper Post Road</a> to Worcester.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Bissell then rode the Lower Post Road,<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> where he headed south into Connecticut, and crossed the Middle Post road at Pomfret. From there, Bissell traveled a road from Norwich to New London.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> After his arrival, colonists and people in neighboring towns were alerted by the firing muskets and ringing of church bells that the war had begun.<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Samuel Parsons of New London added a note, "You will see, by a Letter to your Committee of Correspondence, the necessity of rallying all your forces immediately... We shall march before noon tomorrow."<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194056_38-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194056-38">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> Answering the call, <a href="/wiki/Benedict_Arnold" title="Benedict Arnold">Benedict Arnold</a> of <a href="/wiki/New_Haven,_Connecticut" title="New Haven, Connecticut">New Haven</a>, <a href="/wiki/Israel_Putnam" title="Israel Putnam">Israel Putnam</a> of Pomfret, and others mustered soldiers and headed for Massachusetts.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEStearns196784–87_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEStearns196784–87-54">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> Putnam assembled men for the <a href="/wiki/Connecticut_Militia" class="mw-redirect" title="Connecticut Militia">Connecticut Militia</a>, commanded them on their march to Boston, and arrived there at dawn. Benedict formed a group of soldiers in New Haven, including <a href="/wiki/Yale_College" title="Yale College">Yale College</a> students and soldiers from the <a href="/wiki/Governor%27s_Guards" title="Governor&#39;s Guards">Connecticut State Guards</a>, and followed Putnam to battle.<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG/220px-Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG" decoding="async" width="220" height="146" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG/330px-Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG/440px-Fraunces_Tavern_Block.JPG 2x" data-file-width="4288" data-file-height="2848" /></a><figcaption><a href="/wiki/Fraunces_Tavern" title="Fraunces Tavern">Fraunces Tavern</a> in <a href="/wiki/Lower_Manhattan" title="Lower Manhattan">Lower Manhattan</a>, a meeting place of the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_Sixty" title="Committee of Sixty">Committee of Sixty</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>A riot erupted in <a href="/wiki/Manhattan" title="Manhattan">Manhattan</a>, <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York City</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;t&#93;</a></sup> with news of the battles in Lexington and Concord.<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The colonists seized arms at <a href="/wiki/New_York_City_Hall#18th_century" title="New York City Hall">City Hall</a> and supplies destined for Boston. The patriots set two sloops on fire, closed the <a href="/wiki/Port_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey" title="Port of New York and New Jersey">port</a>, and took possession of the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Custom_House_(New_York_City)" title="United States Custom House (New York City)">Custom House</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Men joined the militia.<sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> By the time the news of the Lexington Alarm made it to Philadelphia, 50,000 armed colonists marched for Boston.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194056_38-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194056-38">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> In Philadelphia, 8,000 people assembled when they heard the ringing of the <a href="/wiki/Liberty_Bell" title="Liberty Bell">Liberty Bell</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bissell returned to Connecticut.<sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> Copies of the manuscript were sent to other locations, like Maryland, North Carolina, and other areas.  See this <a href="/wiki/File:Bissel-Israel.png" title="File:Bissel-Israel.png">notice printed in Baltimore</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194056–78_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194056–78-56">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Two_post_riders_named_Bissell">Two post riders named Bissell</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Two post riders named Bissell"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p><a href="/wiki/Isaac_Bissell" title="Isaac Bissell">Isaac Bissell</a> took a westerly route in Massachusetts, from Worcester, down to Hartford, and then throughout the Connecticut countryside for a total of six days.<sup id="cite_ref-McKenna_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-McKenna-57">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> The dispatch that Isaac carried to Springfield identifies him as the bearer.<sup id="cite_ref-CVHS_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CVHS-58">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Israel Bissell spread the word about the start of the war. His usual mail route was from Boston to New York.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434–436_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434–436-59">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;u&#93;</a></sup> The dispatch carried by Israel Bissell through Connecticut and to New York identified him as the bearer.<sup id="cite_ref-NY_notice_14-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NY_notice-14">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> The copy of the call to arms that arrived in Philadelphia identified the bearer as Trail Bisel or Bisiel.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194050_51-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194050-51">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="The_war_and_after">The war and after</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: The war and after"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>After completing his ride, Bissell returned to Connecticut, where he joined the army alongside his brother, Justis.<sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> They both were among the men from <a href="/wiki/East_Windsor,_Connecticut" title="East Windsor, Connecticut">East Windsor, Connecticut</a>, who served under Captain Wolcott.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEJohnston1889618_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEJohnston1889618-62">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> His father, Israel Sr. also served in the war. The younger Israel served in June 1775, in Captain Stoughton's company, and, in 1776, he served under Captain Wolcott<sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> for one month.<sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> His father died in 1776,<sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and Bissell returned to the family home to take care of the farm.<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>After the war, Bissell moved to <a href="/wiki/Middlefield,_Massachusetts" title="Middlefield, Massachusetts">Middlefield, Massachusetts</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-Weber_44-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Weber-44">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> where he became a sheep farmer.<sup id="cite_ref-DAR_marker_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DAR_marker-63">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> Bissell married Lucy Hancock of Longmeadow, who gave birth to four children.<sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Bissell, his wife, and three children moved to a farm in <a href="/wiki/Hinsdale,_Massachusetts" title="Hinsdale, Massachusetts">Hinsdale, Massachusetts</a> in 1790.<sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965436_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965436-64">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup> Bissell died there on October 24, 1823,<sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and he was buried in the Maple Street Cemetery in Hinsdale.<sup id="cite_ref-CSAR_3-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CSAR-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Daughters_of_the_American_Revolution" title="Daughters of the American Revolution">Daughters of the American Revolution</a> placed a historical marker beside his grave in 1967.<sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> Printed on the marker is "In Memory of Israel Bissell, post-rider from Lexington to Philadelphia alerting towns of the British attack at Lexington April 19, 1775."<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Isadore Goodman of Pittsfield donated the former Israel Bissell homestead to the Conservation Commission of Hinsdale to be used as a historical memorial.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Legacy">Legacy</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Legacy"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Hinsdale historian Marion Ransford reported that the Daughters of the American Revolution installed a special marker at Bissell's grave.<sup id="cite_ref-DAR_marker_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DAR_marker-63">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the late 1990s, <a href="/wiki/David_Wells_Roth" title="David Wells Roth">David Roth</a> artists made paintings for the  Union Oyster House of Boston of historical figures including Israel Bissell.<sup id="cite_ref-Francoeur_20-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Francoeur-20">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="In_popular_culture">In popular culture</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: In popular culture"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Bissell was the subject of "Ride, Israel, Ride", an epic poem by Marie Rockwood of <a href="/wiki/Stockbridge,_Massachusetts" title="Stockbridge, Massachusetts">Stockbridge, Massachusetts</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><i>The remarkable ride of Israel Bissell</i> is a partly fictional account of Bissell's ride written by Alice Schick, Marjorie N. Allen, and Joel Schick in 1976.<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Gerard Chapman wrote the poem, "Listen my children and you shall hear of Israel Bissell of yesteryear, a poet-less patriot whose fame, I fear, was eclipsed by that of Paul Revere."<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Bissell was portrayed by David Bluvband on the cult public access program, <i><a href="/wiki/The_Chris_Gethard_Show" title="The Chris Gethard Show">The Chris Gethard Show</a></i> in the episode "<a href="/wiki/List_of_The_Chris_Gethard_Show_episodes" title="List of The Chris Gethard Show episodes">18th Century American Gladiators</a>", which aired in August 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-68" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-68">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS"><span title="This claim needs references to better sources. (March 2024)">better&#160;source&#160;needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>Bissel was mentioned in ABC's show, <i>American Housewife</i>, Season 5 Episode 2.<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: See also"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<dl><dt>Midnight ride of April 18, 1775</dt></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Paul_Revere" title="Paul Revere">Paul Revere</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/William_Dawes" title="William Dawes">William Dawes</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Samuel_Prescott" title="Samuel Prescott">Samuel Prescott</a></li></ul>
<dl><dt>Danbury, Connecticut ride of April 26, 1777</dt></dl>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Sybil_Ludington" title="Sybil Ludington">Sybil Ludington</a></li></ul>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Israel_Bissell&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Notes"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<div class="reflist reflist-lower-alpha">
<div class="mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns"><ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Phillip Mack Smith raises the question, was the rider Israel or Israel Sr.? Both fought in the war. Smith is the brother of Edward Church Smith, who wrote <i>The History of Middlefield, Mass.</i><sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The Israel Bissell of this article is referred to as a 23-year-old man at the time of the ride.<sup id="cite_ref-RDH_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-RDH-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Bissell was said to be a member of the Committee of Safety,<sup id="cite_ref-Costanzo_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Costanzo-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> but its eleven members at the beginning of 1775 were <a href="/wiki/Benjamin_Church_(physician)" title="Benjamin Church (physician)">Benjamin Church</a>, Richard Devens, Jabez Fisher, <a href="/wiki/John_Hancock" title="John Hancock">John Hancock</a>, <a href="/wiki/William_Heath" title="William Heath">William Heath</a>, <a href="/wiki/Azor_Orne" title="Azor Orne">Azor Orne</a>, <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Palmer_(American_Revolutionary_War_general)" title="Joseph Palmer (American Revolutionary War general)">Joseph Palmer</a>, <a href="/wiki/John_Pigeon" title="John Pigeon">John Pigeon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Joseph_Warren" title="Joseph Warren">Joseph Warren</a>, Abraham Watson, and Benjamin White.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194058–59_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194058–59-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Sons of the Revolution state that the route was 350 miles (560&#160;km).<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Hunt said that the journey was 400 miles (640&#160;km).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-19"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Traditionally, Bissell was said to have arrived in Worcester before noon, which would have meant that he covered 36 miles (58&#160;km) in about two hours, which Scheide said would not have been feasible.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> There was a  kind of horse, now extinct, that were bred for speed. The <a href="/wiki/Narragansett_Pacer" title="Narragansett Pacer">Narragansett Pacer</a>, "according to accounts, [could] travel 100 miles (160&#160;km) in one day".<sup id="cite_ref-Huberdeau_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Huberdeau-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-22">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Also see Smith's article, which states that the horse's fate was documented in an old history of Worcester County.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESmith195642_10-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTESmith195642-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The map between pp. 60 and 61 of <i>The Lexington Alarm</i> identifies the towns that received the Lexington Alarm messages in April and May 1775.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194060–61_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194060–61-27">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-31"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-31">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The Worcester Society of Antiquity states that Bissell left Watertown at 9 a.m. Captain <a href="/wiki/Timothy_Bigelow_(soldier)" title="Timothy Bigelow (soldier)">Timothy Bigelow</a>, and a little later, those under Captain <a href="/wiki/Benjamin_Flagg" class="mw-redirect" title="Benjamin Flagg">Benjamin Flagg</a>, for a total of 110 troops, set off for Lexington and Concord. They learned that the British returned to their camp in Boston. Hearing that news, they turned towards <a href="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">Cambridge</a>, just outside of Boston. Bissell is referred to as Israel and Trail.<sup id="cite_ref-Nutt_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Nutt-29">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-32"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-32">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">From the Norwich attestation, there was no time or day indicated for Worcester.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194063_16-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194063-16">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">There are no official attestations that show that <a href="/wiki/Pomfret,_Connecticut" title="Pomfret, Connecticut">Pomfret, Connecticut</a>, received the news with the first express. There was an update about the state of the war sent in a second Lexington Alarm update, which was likely an oral update on April 20 at 3 p.m. The notice had updated information about the Battle at Concord.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–66_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194065–66-33">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> The second express did not make it to Norwich until the morning of April 21.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-37"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">There is a copy of the handwritten document between pages 50 and 51.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194050–51_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194050–51-36">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup> Governor <a href="/wiki/Jonathan_Trumbull" title="Jonathan Trumbull">Jonathan Trumbull</a> was in Norwich when the town received news that the war had begun.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194064_35-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194064-35">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> Trumbull returned to his house in Lebanon and set up a supply depot at his store, which became the "war office". He asked express riders to get an update on the war before he convened a state assembly meeting.<sup id="cite_ref-SAR_alarm_1-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SAR_alarm-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-39"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">At New London, a message was added to the notice to stop in Saybrook and East Haddam.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194056_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194056-38">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-41"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-41">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">There is no attestation of when the message was received in New Haven, but it is there that a message was added to the dispatch to ride to Philadelphia.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194057_24-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194057-24">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-43"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-43">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Chapman said that Bissell arrived at the Merchant's Coffee House on Wall Street at noon.<sup id="cite_ref-Chapman2_18-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman2-18">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-46"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-46">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The dispatch was addressed to Captain <a href="/wiki/Isaac_Sears" title="Isaac Sears">Isaac Sears</a> (of the Committee of Sixty).<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMerritt194690_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMerritt194690-45">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> Bissell met with the <a href="/wiki/Committee_of_Sixty" title="Committee of Sixty">Committee of Sixty</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> General McDougall ordered for the rider to ride through the night and early morning of April 24. The message from New York also asked the rider to stop in New Brunswick and Elizabethtown in New Jersey.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-47"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-47">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The time of arrival is not know, but McDougall ordered for the rider to ride through the night and early morning of April 24.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194068_25-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194068-25">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-48"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-48">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Elias_Boudinot" title="Elias Boudinot">Elias Boudinot</a> noted in his diary that Bissell had delivered the dispatch.<sup id="cite_ref-FOD_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOD-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-50"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-50">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Bissell's name was spelled "Irael Bissel" by Fairfield and "Trail Bissel" at Trenton.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMerritt194693,_97–100_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMerritt194693,_97–100-49">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-52"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-52">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The copy of the call to arms that arrived in Philadelphia identified the bearer as Trail Bisel or Bisiel.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194050_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194050-51">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Taft said that Bissell arrived at High Street in the morning.<sup id="cite_ref-Taft_9-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Taft-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Hunt states that Bissell arrived in Philadelphia before midnight on April 23.<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434_2-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHunt1965434-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> A copy of the handwritten document is in the collection of the <a href="/wiki/Historical_Society_of_Pennsylvania" title="Historical Society of Pennsylvania">Historical Society of Pennsylvania</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Chapman_4-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Chapman-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEScheide194050_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-FOOTNOTEScheide194050-51">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-55"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The riot was a sign of things to come with the <a href="/wiki/New_York_and_New_Jersey_campaign#Capture_of_New_York_City" title="New York and New Jersey campaign">Capture of New York City</a>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-61"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-61">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">McKenna states that there are no vital records about Israel Bissell or records that he delivered messages about the Lexington Alarm.<sup id="cite_ref-McKenna_57-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-McKenna-57">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> The Israel Bissell article documents his early life, father and brother, and that <a href="/wiki/Elias_Boudinot" title="Elias Boudinot">Elias Boudinot</a> wrote in his diary that he had met Israel Bissell in Elizabethtown, New Jersey, and he was a post rider for the British, and then for the patriots.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
